The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                               The City Diary
                Calcutta High Court on Friday gave three weeks to the state government to implement its hawker policy. The ruling followed petitioner Subhas Duttas allegation that the government had failed to implement its policy, announced three years ago, that no hawkers would be allowed on the pavements of eight streets in the central business district.    New Market police busted a fake currency racket and intercepted Shahjahan Mohammad at the Jawaharlal Nehru Road-Lindsay Street crossing late on Thursday. A sum of Rs 35,000 in fake currency was seized from him. Shahjahan is from Darbhanga, in Bihar.    Suchitra Sens condition remained unchanged on Friday. She will have to be bed-ridden for a few more days, as the knee pain has not subsided. Physiotherapy is continuing. Her breathing has improved.    Ramakrishna Math will celebrate the 173rd birth anniversary of Sri Sri Ramakrishna Dev from 4.30am at Belur Math on Sunday. A festival and a fair will be held on March 16. The West Bengal Surface Transport Corporation will run a special launch service to Belur Math on Sunday and March 16.    Train services on Eastern Railways Sealdah-Dankuni section were disrupted on Friday after a mob blocked the tracks at Bally Ghat station from 9.25am to 12.30pm to protest the late running of a train. The mob also ransacked the station masters office. Two express trains were diverted.                                                                                                                                                                
